<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-486-267  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 486 267.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  Nov 1990 v7 n11 p198(11).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Accounting grows up. (accounting packages for the Macintosh arerated)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Slay, Alan L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The accounting software now available for the Macintosh has grownto such an extent that the market now accommodates both low-endsingle-user and high-end multi-user packages.andP;  Five categories ofaccounting programs are surveyed.andP;  The first, PersonalApplications, includes personal bookkeeping programs, aimed at thesmall business and single-user markets and offering just incomeand expense categories.andP;  The second, Excel-Template Applications,includes programs that run under Microsoft Excel.andP;  The third,One-Write Applications, use the manual one-write system as theirmodel, entering financial data twice, firstly as a payment amount,and secondly as a category charge.andP;  The fourth, All-In-OneApplications.andP;  The fifth, Separate-Module Applications, includethose programs aimed at full-time bookkeepers, many offeringmulti-user capabilities.andP;  The discussion concludes with acheck-list for buying the right program.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AccountingMultiuser SoftwareFinancial SoftwareSoftware Selection.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Accounting programs compared. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>